<h4 id="history">History</h4>
<ol>
  <li>differential geometry: is calculus and analytic geometry applied to curves and surfaces.</li>
  <li>Curvature: the key concept through differential geometry, first, curves curvature, then surfaces
curvature, and high-dimensional objects curvature.</li>
</ol>

<h4 id="big-name">Big Name</h4>
<ol>
  <li>Huygens: 1673</li>
  <li>All involutes of a curve are disjoint, means they don’t cross each other.</li>
  <li>They are perpendicular to the tangent line.</li>
</ol>

<h4 id="curvature-definition-one">Curvature Definition one</h4>
<p>line $NQ$ and line $CP$ are the normal line of the curve at point P and Q. the two normals will 
meet in some point,  as P and Q get closer and closer, the intersection of the two normal line
stablized. and it is the limit value, and the limit point is called the center of the curvature.
when P 
<img src="/images/space-differential-geometry-history-curvature.png" /></p>

<h4 id="curvature-definition-two">Curvature Definition two</h4>
<p>Osculating Circle of point P at curve C.</p>

<p>The evolute of an involute is the original curve.
